'''Avi Shlaim''' (born October 31, 1945 in [[Baghdad]]) is an [[Israel]]i-[[United Kingdom|British]] dual citizen and [[history|historian]] and identifies ethnically as an [[Iraqi Jew]].<ref name=attapatu>{{cite web|title=Interview with Middle East Scholar Avi Shlaim: America, Israel, and the Middle East|author=Don Attapattu|publisher=The Nation|date=June 16, 2004|url=http://www.thenation.com/doc/20040628/attapatu}}</ref> He is considered a key member of a group of Israeli scholars known as the [[New Historians]] who put forward revised interpretations of the history of [[Zionism]] and [[Israel]]. He is a regular contributor to ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper. According to [[The Nation]] magazine, "he is widely regarded one of the world's leading authorities on the Israeli-Arab conflict."<ref name=attapatu/>

Shlaim studied history at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]], then taught International Relations at [[Reading University]], specializing in European issues. His deep academic interest in the history of Israel began in 1987, when he took a position as a British Academy Research Professor at [[St. Antony's College, Oxford]]. <ref name=rapaport>{{cite web|title=No Peaceful Solution|author=Miron Rapaport|publisher=Ha'aretz Friday Supplement|date=11.08.2005|url=http://www.editriceilponte.org/_files/HaaretzInterviewEnglish.pdf}}</ref>

==Methodology & Works==

Shlaim's approach to the study of history is informed by his belief that "The job of the historian is to judge." <ref name=rapaport/>

His books include ''Collusion across the Jordan'' (winner of the [[1988]] Political Studies Association's W. J. M. Mackenzie Prize); ''The Politics of Partition'' ([[1990]] and [[1998]]); ''War and Peace in the Middle East: A Concise History'' ([[1995]]), ''The Cold War and the Middle East'' (co-editor, [[1997]]), and ''The Iron Wall: Israel and the Arab World'' ([[2001]]).

